It’s the most wonderful time of the year. Hello, December! 💙✨💙 I shot this image at an angle to showcase the houses out back, but also to switch it up from the traditional post looking straight down the dock. It’s hard to do something different at a location that many have shot over the years, but I do try to change something so I do not have the same image as everyone else. I have shots of this at night as well, but prefer to have the twilight glow so I intentionally went up for blue hour. Shot last year on my 15-30 mm. 
.
.
.

Community Boating’s holiday boat is back for the season. No Rudolph again this year. I shot this at twilight so I would get the burn on the horizon and pretty twinkle of lights. Taken on a 15-30 mm, no filter and did a long exposure with intentions of smoothing down that water! ✨Longfellow Bridge lights are back on (they were off for a short while). 
.

December’s cold moon (99.5%) rising behind the iconic Zakim Bridge. I chose my spot specifically for the moon passing behind the bridge. My two favorites in one image, Lenny and a moon! 🌝One shot, no photoshop shenanigans. I still haven’t learned how to use PS. Every year I say I’ll learn and the thought of spending more time on a computer is a no for me. I started photography in 1995, we didn’t have the options we do now so I am out there killing myself to get it right in camera. 😂
.
.

Gloucester’s lobster trap tree is lit and looking awesome. They really outdid themselves this year. I’ve been shooting this tree for 6 years and look forward to seeing what they do each time. They get better and better! They haven’t done the doorway in a few years so when I pulled up Saturday night, I was in awe (it’s the little things for me in life). The inside is truly art, see image 2. Gloucester takes great pride in this tradition, as they should. This is one of my favorite coastal towns, so rich in history, amazing beaches, and full of great people. 🦞Gloucester, this is truly a piece of art and thank you for keeping this tradition for everyone to enjoy. 
.
.

The crescent passed behind the Pru right at peak sunrise colors. These are the mornings that make all the failed attempts worth it. 🌙 No, this is not fake or photoshopped.

A nearly full rising moon over Boston’s Museum of Science. 🌝 I saw a clearing on the horizon and took off for this shot. I get there, a larger cloud mass moves in. The clouds were moving a lot faster than the moon and building as it was rising. I saw a piece of the moon here and there but mostly buried behind clouds. If you were raised here, surely you have many memories of the MOS as a kid! I have vivid memories of the musical stairs, the Omni theater and the lightning show. 😃
.

Made the trek to Whaleback Light yesterday for the polar vortex. ❄️ Extreme weather always makes for the best images. I shot this just as the sun was transitioning into the scene. I loved the drama of the smoke building and the soft tones. I was probably the only one shooting at a high shutter to capture birds crossing the frame, but I got them! Pleasure finally meeting @photosbykeri18 and always a good time bumping into @robwrightimages! 
.

Spring in Boston! 🌸 It’s been a while since I posted. Took a much needed break from the cityscapes to photograph owls, learned to drone, studied and passed the FAA’s 107 exam and then changed jobs. I took a job out of Colorado, so I’ll get to visit Denver and share my heart with a new city. I am looking forward to shooting Spring blooms on the drone this year. I’ve been a photographer for many years, it was time to expand my portfolio and try something new. Image shot in 2022. 
.

Another trip around the sun today. 🎂I figured one of my macro photos was fitting for today, since this is where it all began. This is the happiest I’ve ever been. I finally learned to let go of what wasn’t right. It meant starting over in every aspect of my life. Learn to walk away from the things that don’t make you happy. In the end, they won’t matter. A year ago I’d never think I’d be at a new job, traveling to Denver, learning to drone with a wonderful community, and still loving all things creatively as an artist. Thank you, everyone, for supporting me. I’ve met a lot of beautiful people in my journey. 
.

Last night’s storm over Boston. ⚡️Was out there for 3 hours and it was awesome. A storm dictates where you stand and you move, a lot. I follow radar while I’m out to help me understand the timing and what direction to face. I have a lightning app that sends signals to my iwatch so I am aware of how close they are, and where. I set the camera to run continuously and did both video and images last night. Amazing how many attempts it takes. The chase of capturing lightning the honest way is so much fun. It’s never easy, but it’s worth it. 
.

Last night’s rising Sturgeon supermoon! 🌝 I decided to do a rule of thirds composition rather than the traditional moon directly behind a lighthouse. Did my usual sprinting up the street, decided I didn’t like my comp, sprinted back up the street, and had to shoot through someone’s yard around shrubs. Not to be misconstrued with me standing in their yard, I was in the street. I learned my lesson many years ago, and that was to move a lot when you shoot. Last night, my image didn’t matter as much as my family. They were all there with me, probably eye rolling over me spazzing out. We may not have it all, but together we have everything. 💙
.
.

Summer storms over Boston! ⚡️Shot this during that Friday night storm where the lightning lasted for about 4 hours. I tried so hard to get a big bolt with the Pru, but this was the best I got. I was out there for the entire storm hoping. I left my camera running on continuous/burst mode doing brief long exposures almost the entire time as I didn’t have a trigger then. Lightning is so very difficult to capture (the honest way), am shocked I even got this, but my efforts were truly there. I cropped this way down so you can see the details, bigger bolts were out of frame, so frustrating. ⚡️💙⚡️
.

Boston Common Carousel. 🎠 I love carousels, probably because I love color, art and animals. I don’t go on them because they make me nauseous going in circles and forget it if it goes backwards! I shot this right after a beautiful sunset so I got the jewel tones in the sky. This is a 15 second exposure so people do not appear in my shot. The starbursts are created by the blades in a lens. I loved the colors on the sand and the curling waves so I knew my image needed to incorporate both. Not the easiest shot, but I realized a long time ago that I could never grow as an artist if I was never challenging myself. 💜

Good morning, Boston. 🌙 My favorite moon phase is the crescent during twilight solely for the colors. It doesn’t always work out, but I am out a lot hustling all over the city so eventually I will get the shot I want. This was a waning 5.7% so a tiny sliver that faded out as the sun came up. So beautiful!

Happy Thanksgiving!🍁🦃 🍁Today feels a little more special than others. This year brought so many challenges and tears. I uprooted my life, changed my career path and now share a life between Denver and Boston. Both parents were hospitalized this year, and today I get to hug them both. Life has its ebbs and flows but it makes you realize how precious and fragile life truly is. Sending virtual hugs to my BFF’s who carried me through this year (you know who you are since I’ve bombed your inboxes with messages). I love you. Enjoy your day today, remember to eat all the potatoes you can and never refuse the desserts. 😀
.

Gloucester does it again! 🦞I’ve been shooting this tree for a long time and enjoy the tradition of visiting every December. It holds many memories from my childhood. They finally moved this to a much better spot on the water. I had a little model I met, and he understood the assignment when I said to stay still. I exchanged information with his mother and will be sending her some shots, he was too cute! I never take an image of a child without the parent knowing, or asking first.🌲
.
